  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">SHO Covid-19 Vaccination Campaign Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Afghanistan experienced the first wave of pandemics between February - July 2020 and the second wave of the pandemic in mid-October 2020- mid-January 2021. According to Dr. Majrooh, the Minister of Public Health, the third wave of the virus has been detected across the nation, and that the infections are moving from east to west. As of 24 May 2021, the country has registered 66, 903 cases and 2,836 of deaths due to COVID-19. Observers and health experts believe the real number of infections could be much higher as the current figures could have been under-reported due to not having enough testing and tracing capacity across the country. 
A seroprevalence survey, conducted by MoPH, shows that in total 31.5 % of the population of Afghanistan have been infected. To manage and prevent the further spread of COVID-19, the country has applied approaches for controlling the disease such as surveillance, case detection and isolation, handwashing, respiratory hygiene, use of face masks, and social distancing. However, due to the social and economic impacts, the proposed approaches are either not practiced widely or are observed only for a short period of time. With the current measures in place and the level of practice, it seems the disease is still spreading rapidly among the whole population. While all protective measures are important, the introduction of the COVID-19 vaccine, particularly among the high-risk/vulnerable groups, will help control the pandemic in Afghanistan. So far, Afghanistan received 968,000 doses of vaccine. The vaccination campaign has started, and data shows that a total of 573 K of vaccine doses have been administered and 96,910 people (0.3% of the total population) fully vaccinated up to 25 May 2021.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Size of the population in targeted geographical areas: 117,6792
Estimate beneficiaries you intend to reach directly: 611,932 and indirectly: 564,860</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To contribute to reducing COVID-19 related morbidity and mortality by rolling out a vaccination campaign in five target provinces of Afghanistan.</narrative>
  </description>
